WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.640 --> 00:00:06.799
My name is Guy Morgan.

2
00:00:06.799 --> 00:00:09.080
One way or another,
I've been involved

3
00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:12.039
in the arts for more
than six decades.

4
00:00:12.039 --> 00:00:17.480
I know ideas are fleeting,
but nowadays, art is momentary too.

5
00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:22.239
It's there, and
then just disappears.

6
00:00:22.239 --> 00:00:24.879
This led me to ask
some brilliant artists

7
00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:27.839
what they think about.

8
00:00:31.079 --> 00:00:33.600
What do you wish for as an artist?

9
00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:36.119
(GUITAR MUSIC)

10
00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:46.079
WOMAN 1: To create works
that matter.

11
00:00:55.920 --> 00:00:58.679
WOMAN 2: That my work
will be remembered.

12
00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:08.079
WOMAN 3: When I was at
uni, all I wanted was fame

13
00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:16.040
and now I'm in the industry,
all I need is money.

14
00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:27.920
WOMAN 4: Creative Freedom.

15
00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:34.840
GUY: What experiences within the
art community have helped you most?

16
00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:43.239
MAN 1: Painting Del Kathryn Barton
for the Archibald Prize.

17
00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:54.439
WOMAN 1: When I felt
wanted and valued.

18
00:02:00.439 --> 00:02:03.200
WOMAN 5: Finding a strong,
inclusive community.

19
00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:07.400
GUY: What language or
words do you object to

20
00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:10.120
when people talk about your work?

21
00:02:13.879 --> 00:02:15.439
WOMAN 2: Pretty.

22
00:02:22.599 --> 00:02:24.680
WOMAN 5: Tokenistic.

23
00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:25.919
Difficult.

24
00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:39.479
AI VOICE: The judges had
a very difficult task.

25
00:02:39.479 --> 00:02:41.360
It was very competitive.

26
00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:48.159
GUY: What are the most challenging
issues you face as an artist?

27
00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:53.960
WOMAN 2: Lack of opportunities
for experimental artwork.

28
00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:05.759
AI VOICE: Not being taken
seriously as an artist.

29
00:03:13.199 --> 00:03:17.120
MAN 2: Society excludes me
through structured inequality.

30
00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:21.319
GUY: What would create
more equal opportunities

31
00:03:21.319 --> 00:03:22.879
for you in the art world?

32
00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:29.520
MAN 2: Make access funding
the last thing to get cut.

33
00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:32.120
Not the first.

34
00:03:38.159 --> 00:03:41.759
WOMAN 6: The publishing
industry needs to catch up.

35
00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.680
GUY: What barriers to participation
in the arts would you like removed?

36
00:03:49.759 --> 00:03:51.560
AI VOICE: Labelling
and expectations.

37
00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:08.400
AI VOICE: Society needs to work out
how to make society less disabling.

38
00:04:14.759 --> 00:04:17.000
AI VOICE: Not all
disabilities are visual.

39
00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:23.959
WOMAN 5: Misconceptions.

40
00:04:33.639 --> 00:04:35.959
WOMAN 6: Remove all barriers.

41
00:04:38.279 --> 00:04:40.319
GUY: What is the most positive thing

42
00:04:40.319 --> 00:04:43.240
about being an
artist with disability?

43
00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:15.560
WOMAN 7: Community.

44
00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:22.000
AI VOICE: I get to take
part in projects like this.

45
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.040
GUY: What is the
most difficult thing

46
00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:27.199
about being an
artist with disability?

47
00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:30.519
WOMAN 2: Dealing with
health issues daily

48
00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:33.839
when all you want to
do is make your artwork.

49
00:05:37.519 --> 00:05:39.759
AI VOICE: Not being
able to see properly.

50
00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:47.600
GUY: Is there anything
else you'd like to add?

51
00:05:55.279 --> 00:05:59.319
WOMAN 6: Those with disabilities
turn to the arts.

52
00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:11.920
The arts should turn more to us.

53
00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:26.040
WOMAN 3: Artists who identify
as disabled get relegated.

54
00:06:37.759 --> 00:06:40.279
AI VOICE: I stand for inclusion.

55
00:06:40.279 --> 00:06:43.120
Exclusion doesn't right inequality.

56
00:06:52.639 --> 00:06:55.160
WOMAN 1: The arts sector
is in deep need

57
00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:58.800
of cultural and structural change.

58
00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:25.000
GUY: Many thanks to Amy Mills,

59
00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:30.639
Angie Goto, Bridie McKim,
Christine Johnson, Duncan Meerding,

60
00:08:30.639 --> 00:08:35.440
Emily Dash, Matthew Clarke,
Natalia Stawyskyj,

61
00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:39.399
Sandra Minchin and Sri Thulin.

